Collections

built-in class

(1) create
    - emptyList() returns empty, immutable list
    - emptySet() returns empty, immutable set
    - emptyMap() returns empty, immutable map
    - singletonList(T o) returns an immutable list containing only o
    - singleton(T o) returns an immutable set containing only o
    - singletonMap(K key, V val) returns an immutable map containing only the specified entry
    - nCopies(int n, T o) returns immutable list consisting of n copies of o
(2) add
    - addAll(Collection<? super T> c, T... elems) adds elems to the end of c and returns boolean
        - useful to to add multiple single elems or an array of single elems
(3) retrieve
    - max(Collection<? extends T> c, Comparator<? super T> comp) returns max elem
        - comp: func (optional)
    - min(Collection<? extends T> c, Comparator<? super T> comp) returns min elem
    - indexOfSubList(List<?> src, List<?> target) returns starting pos of 1st occurrence of target within src
        - if no such occurrence, returns -1
    - lastIndexOfSublist(List<?> src, List<?> target) returns starting pos of last occurrence
(4) modify
    - fill(List<? super T> ls, T o) replaces all elems of ls with o
    - rotate(List<?> ls, int distance) rotates elems in list by distance
    - shuffle(List<?> ls, Random rand) randomly permutes ls using rand (optional)
    - swap(List<?> ls, int i, int j) swaps elems at indices i and j in ls
    - reverse(List<?> ls) reverses ls
    - replaceAll(List<T> ls, T old, T nw) replaces all occurrences of old in ls with nw and returns boolean
        - if ls contained one or more elems equal to old, returns true 
(5) search
    - binarySearch(List<? extends T> ls, T key, Comparator<? super T> comp) returns index of key in ls
        - if key is not present, returns -1
        - ls must be sorted into a-/descending order prior to making this call
        - comp: comparator used for sorting (optional)
(6) check
    - disjoint(Collection<?> c1, Collection<?> c2) returns true if c1 and c2 have no elems in common
    - frequency(Collection<?> c, Object o) returns number of elems in c equal to o 
(7) sort
    - sort(List<T> ls, Comparator<? super T> comp) sorts ls according to comp (optional)
(8) utils
    - copy(List<? super T> dest, List<? extends T> src) copies all elems from src into dest
    - reverseOrder() returns comparator that imposes the reverse of the natural ordering
    - reverseOrder(Comparator<T> comp) returns comparator that imposes the reverse ordering of comparator

EXAMPLE
(1)
List<Integer> ls = new ArrayList<>(Collections.nCopies(2, 1));
ls.addAll(Collections.nCopies(2, 2)); // ls = [1, 1, 2, 2]
(2)
Collections.addAll(ls, 3, 3); // ls = [1, 1, 2, 2, 3, 3]
(4)
List<String> l = new ArrayList<>(List.of("b", "c", "d", "e", "a"));
Collections.rotate(l, 1); // l = [a, b, c, d, e]
List<String> sub = l.subList(1, 4); // sub = [b, c, d]
Collections.rotate(sub, -1); // l =  [a, c, d, b, e]
(5+7)
Collections.sort(l); // l = [a, b, c, d, e]
int x = Collections.binarySearch(l, "b"); // x = 1
(6)
int y = Collections.frequency(List.of(1, 1, 2, 3), 1); // y = 2
(8)
String[] a = new String[]{"doe", "joe"};
Arrays.sort(a, Collections.reverseOrder()); // a = [joe, doe]
